"content": "To solve the problem of reconstructing a valid sequence of sibling-merge operations, we must first understand the nature of the operation. A sibling-merge operation takes two adjacent siblings in a tree and merges them into a single node, effectively making their children the children of the new merged node. However, the problem description implies a specific structure: we are transforming an initial tree into a final tree by merging siblings. 1. Algorithmic Derivation. Data Structures: Tree Representation (adjacency lists), Stack/Queue, Parent-Child Mapping. Logic: The final tree is a compressed version of the initial tree. Every node in the final tree corresponds to a set of nodes in the initial tree that were merged. 1. Identify Node Correspondence: A node u in T_final corresponds to a contiguous range of siblings in T_init. 2. Recursive Traversal (DFS): Perform a DFS on T_final. For each node u in T_final, identify its children. These children must correspond to a sequence of nodes in T_init. 3. Operation Sequence: A merge operation is defined by the pair of siblings being merged. We use a greedy approach: for a set of siblings s_1, s_2, ..., s_m in T_init, if they are meant to be represented by k nodes in T_final, we perform m-k merge operations. Complexity Analysis: Time Complexity O(N), Space Complexity O(N). 2. Step-by-Step Logic for Reconstruction: 1. Map each node in T_final to its representative node in T_init. 2. For each node u in T_init, look at its children. 3. Group these children based on which node in T_final they belong to. 4. If a group contains x children from T_init, it requires x-1 merge operations. 5. The order of operations must respect the tree structure. 3. Final Answer Derivation: The solution is the sequence of pairs (u, v) representing the nodes being merged.",
"orchestration_decision": "execute_locally"
}

